<subsection><title> Orphaned Content </title>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            This is just a place to put content that was written and may or not be used.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <p>
		When leanring a new concept, it is typically a good strategy to compare it to things that you already know. To understand what a differential equation is, it makes sense to show it differs from a regular equation. For example, consider the equation
		<men xml:id="a1">
			x^2 + 3 = 7
		</men>,
		and solve for <m>x</m>. This is done by isolating <m>x</m> using a sequence of algebra rules, like so
		<md>
			<mrow> 	x^2 + 3 	\amp= 7 		\amp 											</mrow>
			<mrow> 	x^2 		\amp= 4 		\amp (\text{subtract both sides by } 3)			</mrow>
			<mrow> 	\sqrt{x^2} 	\amp= \sqrt{4} 	\amp (\text{take square root of both sides})	</mrow>
			<mrow> 	x 			\amp= \pm 2 	\amp (\text{simplify})							</mrow>
		</md>
		and we say <m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=2</m> are solutions.
	</p>

	<p>
		Now, consider solving for <m>y</m> in the equation 
		<men xml:id="a2">
			y + 3x = 7
		</men>. 
		This time we isolate <m>y</m>, 
		<md>
			<mrow> 	y + 3x	 	\amp= 7 		\amp 											</mrow>
			<mrow> 	y 			\amp= 7 - 3x 	\amp (\text{subtract both sides by } 3x)		</mrow>
		</md>
		and we say <m>y=7-3x</m> is the solution.
	</p>

	<p>
		Finally, consider solving for <m>y</m> in the equation 
		<men xml:id="d1">
			y^\prime + 3x = 7
		</men>. 
		As before, let's try to isolate <m>y</m>, 
		<md>
			<mrow> 	y^\prime + 3x	 	\amp= 7 		\amp 											</mrow>
			<mrow> 	y^\prime 			\amp= 7 - 3x 	\amp (\text{subtract both sides by } 3x)		</mrow>
		</md>
		but how do we get <m>y</m> from this point? If you look carefully, <m>y</m> must be the function you take the derivative of to get <m>7-3x</m>, but this is exactly the anti-derivative of <m>7-3x</m>!
	</p>

	<p>
		So, we can fully isolate <m>y</m> by integrating both sides of the equation, like so
		<md>
			<mrow> \int y^\prime \ dx 	\amp= \int  7 - 3x \ dx	</mrow>
		</md>
	</p>
	
