        <exercise><title> <em>Statement <m>\to</m> Differential Equation</em> </title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Which equation below best represents the statement:
                    <blockquote>
                        <p>
                            The rate of decay of a radioactive substance <m> N </m> is equal to a constant times the amount of the substance.
                        </p>
                    </blockquote>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> N' = kN </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Incorrect. This represents growth, not decay.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> N'' = kN </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Incorrect. This represents a second derivative relationship.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> N' = -kN </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Correct. The rate of decay is equal to a negative constant times the amount of the substance.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> N = kN' </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Incorrect. This does not represent the rate of change.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>
        
        <exercise><title> <em>Statement <m>\to</m> Differential Equation</em> </title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Which equation below best represents the statement:
                    <blockquote>
                        <p>
                            The rate of change of the amount of money <m> M(t) </m> in a bank account is equal to a constant times the amount of money in the account.
                        </p>
                    </blockquote>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> M'(t) = k </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Incorrect. This represents a constant rate of change, not one dependent on the amount of money.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> M(t) = kM'(t) </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Incorrect. This does not represent the rate of change.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> M'(t) = kM(t) </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Correct. The rate of change is equal to a constant times the amount of money in the account.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> M''(t) = kM(t) </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Incorrect. This represents a second derivative relationship.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>
        
        <exercise><title> <em>Statement <m>\to</m> Differential Equation</em> </title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Which equation below best represents the statement:
                    <blockquote>
                        <p>
                            The velocity of an object with position, <m>s(t)</m>, in free fall is equal to a constant times the time <m> t </m>.
                        </p>
                    </blockquote>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> s(t) = gt </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Incorrect. This says the position is equal to a constant times the time.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> s'(t) = gt + C </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Incorrect. The statement says nothing about adding a constant, <m>C</m>.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> s'(t) = gt </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Correct.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m> s''(t) = gt </m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <feedback>
                        <p>
                            Incorrect. <m>s''(t)</m> is acceleration, not velocity.
                        </p>
                    </feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>
    
    </reading-questions>

    <p>
		For the moment, consider the differential equation 
		<men xml:id="variables-eqn1">
			x\frac{dy}{dx} - 2y = 4 - x.
		</men>
		This differential equation has two variables, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>. One of these variables represents the solution (a function) and the other represents the values that you plug into the function. In differential equations, it is important to know which one is which. For our example, <m>y</m>, is the solution and <m>x</m> represents the values we plug into <m>y</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
		It turns out that <m>y(x) = x^2 + x - 2</m> is a solution to <xref ref="variables-eqn1"/> above. 
		<fn>
			The notation, <m>y(x)</m>, is used to indicate that <m>y</m> is a function of <m>x</m>. However, we often drop the "<m>(x)</m>" to shorten the expression
		</fn>
		Let's graph this function by selecting <m>x</m>-values to input into the function giving us some <m>y</m>-values, as shown below.
	</p>

	<p>
		<sidebyside widths="14% 14% 28% 44%" margins="auto" valign="middle">

			<p>
				<p>
					<line> List some </line> 
					<line> <m>x</m> values </line> 
					<line> first <m>\rightarrow</m> </line> 
				</p>
			</p>

			<tabular halign="center">
				<col right="minor" />
				<col />

				<row bottom="minor">
					<cell><m>x</m></cell><cell><m>y</m></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell>-3</cell><cell>3</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell>-2</cell><cell>-1</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell>-1</cell><cell>-3</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell>-0</cell><cell>-3</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell>1</cell><cell>-1</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell>2</cell><cell>3</cell>
				</row>
			</tabular>

			<p>
				<p>
					<line> <m>\leftarrow</m> The <m>y</m> values </line> 
					<line> are <term>dependent</term> </line> 
					<line> on the <m>x</m> values </line> 
				</p>
			</p>
			
			<image>

			<latex-image>
				\begin{tikzpicture}
					\begin{axis}[
						axis x line=center,
						axis y line=center,
						xtick={-3,-2,...,2},
						ytick={-4,-3,...,5},
						xlabel={$x$},
						ylabel={$y$},
						xlabel style={below right},
						ylabel style={above left},
						xmin=-3.5,
						xmax=2.5,
						ymin=-3.5,
						ymax=3.5]
						
						\addplot[only marks]coordinates{
							(-3,3)
							(-2,-1)
							(-1,-3)
							(0,-3)
							(1,-1)
							(2,3)
						};
					\end{axis}
				\end{tikzpicture}
			</latex-image>

			</image>
		
		</sidebyside>
	</p>
	
	<p>
		We graphed this function to emphasize the fact that the <m>y</m>-values could not be found until we had the <m>x</m>-values. In other words, the <m>y</m>-values were <em>dependent</em> on the <m>x</m>-values and the <m>x</m>-values were choosen <em>independently</em> from any other value.
	</p>

	<definition xml:id="def-variable-types"><title> Dependent and Independent Variables </title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				In a differential equation, the <term>dependent variable</term> is the variable that represents the unknown function (i.e., solution). The <term>independent variable</term> represents the variable that the unknown function depends on.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</definition>

	<note xml:id="notes-variables"><title> Useful Facts about Variables </title>
		<ul marker="square">
			<li>The independent variable may or not be present in a differential equation, but a dependent variable must be present.</li>
			<li>If a variable has a derivative applied to it, it must be the dependent variable. The other variable present is the independent variable. </li>
			<li>When we solve a differential equation, the dependent variable is the solution and it will be written as a function of the independent variable. </li>
			<li>In general, if you were plotting a solution to a differential equation, the independent variable would correspond to the <m>x</m>-axis (horizontal) and the dependent variable would correspond to the <m>y</m>-axis (vertical). </li>
		</ul>
	</note>
	
	<p>
		Let's look at a few examples to demonstrate how we identify the dependent and independent variables contained in a differential equation.
	</p>

